
-The bash script "easter" calculates the Greek Orthodox Easter Day (since 1924).

-The bash script "julian" converts a given Gregorian Calendar date (since 1582) 
 to the corresponding date of the Julian Calendar. These two calendars diverge 3
 days every 400 years (on the average almost one day every seven metonic cycles).

 If no date is specified, the script converts the date returned by the bash shell
 command "date" with the following format:
 $ date +"%Y:%m:%d:%H-%M:%j"
 2018-01-29:11-40-029
 $ ./julian
 2018:01:16:11-40:16

 Below are listed a few typical examples:

 $ ./julian --use 2101:01:15:00-01:15
 2101:01:01:00-01:1
 $ ./julian --use 1901:01:15:00-01:15
 1901:01:02:00-01:2
 $ ./julian --use 1801:01:15:00-01:15
 1801:01:03:00-01:3
 $ ./julian --use 1701:01:15:00-01:15
 1701:01:04:00-01:4
 $ ./julian --use 1601:01:15:00-01:15
 1601:01:05:00-01:5
 
 To get the easter date in Julian calendar, one can use the bash command "xargs"; ie: 
 $ ./easter --use 2129 | xargs ./julian --use
 2129:03:27:00-00:86
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


 - The MS Excel (mac 11) file "error".xlsx" is an unproved analysis of the Metonic cycle
   value when applied to the Julian calendar. My estimation is that in the long term it
   can approach the value (6939.75) if the second year of the first cycle is a leap year.

